    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The integer passed to the constructor represents its <strong>initial capacity</strong>, i.e., the number of elements it can hold before it needs to resize its internal array (and has nothing to do with the initial number of elements in the list).</p>\n\n<p>To initialize an list with 60 zeros you do:</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;Integer&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;(Collections.nCopies(60, 0));\n</code></pre>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>If you want to create a list with 60 <em>different</em> objects, you could use the Stream API with a <code>Supplier</code> as follows:</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;Person&gt; persons = Stream.generate(Person::new)\n                             .limit(60)\n                             .collect(Collectors.toList());\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 329612,
      "reputation" : 72239,
      "user_id" : 653230,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adc8afef3a25bf45a31686f786149d0?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "WhiteFang34",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/653230/whitefang34"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 8,
    "last_activity_date" : 1302296271,
    "creation_date" : 1302296271,
    "answer_id" : 5600694,
    "question_id" : 5600668,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The 60 you're passing is just the initial capacity for internal storage. It's a hint on how big you think it might be, yet of course it's not limited by that. If you need to preset values you'll have to set them yourself, e.g.:</p>\n\n<pre><code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; 60; i++) {\n    list.add(0);\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
